sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1321113
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Phytochelatin (PC) EC20 + linker-CBDcipA-linker with LacI promoter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Xenia Spencer-Milnes

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: Scar25 ATG
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This sequence is produced by RFC10-assembly of a RFC10-RBS with a RFC25-prefixed part.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Michael Osthege
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This sequence is produced by an assembly method.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The resulting sequence is a combination of the RFC10 RBS-CDS scar (tactag) and 9 nucleotides from the RFC25 prefix (atg gcc ggc).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1321005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Synthetic Phytochelatin EC(20) rfc25 fusion format
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Xenia Spencer-Milnes
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Sequence is not natural. Basis for the sequence was from the following reference: Bae W, Chen W, Mulchandani A, Mehra RK (2000) Enhanced bioaccumulation of heavy metals by bacterial cells displaying synthetic phytochelatins. Biotechnol Bioeng. 70(5):518-24.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: Scar 25
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is the scar produced by assembly using RFC 25.
If you are assembling a composite part using RFC 25, you can insert this part and specify blunt assembly to get the desired sequence.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1321014
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: CBDCipA with N and C-terminal linker
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This CBD is from the Cellulosomal -scaffolding protein A (cipA) of Clostridium thermocellum including the endogenous linker sequences at the N and C-terminus (UniProt ID Q06851 link http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/Q06851). It is in RFC25 format to allow for easy use in protein fusions. The CBD is part of the CBM3 family (link to cazy http://www.cazy.org/CBM3.html). This CBD has been used in many application: in fusions with cell adhesion peptides to enhance the properties of cellulose as a cell-growth matrix (Andrade et al 2010a, Andrade et al 2010b), fused to enzymes to remove contaminants from water (Kauffmann et al 2000) and fused to an antimicrobial peptide (Ramos, Domingues & Gama 2010). At present the cloning for these constructs is still in progress to correct an illegal EcoRI site which was identified in the parts with this CBD. This can be achieved with a silent mutation via site-directed mutagenesis and we aim to send these parts to the registry once this is complete.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Xenia Spencer-Milnes
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The designed construct was ordered from as a GeneArt?? String (Invitrogen??? Life Technologies).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The DNA sequence from the relevant portion of http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/144777 was codon optimised for ''E.coli''. RFC[25] prefix and suffix were appended to the sequence with an additional 4 basepairs (gatc) at the beginning and end to allow space for the restriction enzymes to bind to the EcoRI and PstI sites at the ends of the sequence for cloning purposes.
